Introduction¶

This data set contains of 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan. Some of the variables include loan amount, borrower rate (interest rate) and borrower income.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

In this data analysis report, we will primarily focus our attention around loans and borrowers. We will explain the dataset by using univariate, bivariate and multivariate visualizations. Throughout this report we will look to answer two research questions:

  • Does it matter who you are for what loan amount you are getting?
  • Who gets the best borrowerrate and why?

Preliminary Wrangling¶

As the main objective of this project is exploratory and explanatory analysis, we will limit the data wrangling to the bare minimum. The data is expected to be of acceptable quality (tidy data) and the wrangling will be done to enable exploratory and explanatory analysis.

Step 1) Gather and load data¶

In [2]:
def load_data(url, filename):
    ''' Function which takes as input a csv file link and csv filename, 
    and returns file returned in the workspace'''
    
    start = time.time()
    response = requests.get(url, stream=True)
    
    if response.status_code == 200:
        with open(filename, mode = 'wb') as file:
            file.write(response.content)
        print(f"CSV file downloaded and saved as {filename}")
    else:
        print(f"Failed to download CSV file. status code: {response.status_code}")
    
    end = time.time()
    print(f'Download Time: {end-start:.2f} seconds.')

The structure of the dataset¶

113937 rows, 81 columns

Main feature(s) of interest¶

  • Loan original amount = The origination amount of the loan
  • Borrower rate = The borrowers interest rate for this loan

Supporting features in data exploration¶

  • Income range = The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created

  • Is borrower homeowner = A borrower will be classified as homeowner if they have a mortage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner

  • Loan status = The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue.

  • Loan origination date = The date the loan was originated.

  • Occupation = The occupation selected by the borrower at the time they created the listing

  • Employment status = The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing

  • Stated monthly income = The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created

  • Debt to income ratio = Debt/income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is null if the debt/income ratio is not available and is capped at 10.01 (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%)

  • and more...

Let's start by exploring our dataset to decide what needs to be cleaned and which transformations are required.

We printed a lot of statistics above and will go through it here.

Data structure

By scimming the columns we get the impression of tidy data. This is because each column is a variable, each row is an observation and each type of observational unit forms a table. Most of the dates seen in the dataframe are timestamps. We are likely more interested in daily or less granular data, but that's not an issue. Every header is in in CamelCase style without spaces and we will leave it like that.

Data quality

  • Duplicates: 0
  • There is approximately 113k rows in the dataframe. Some columns have too many NAs and will be removed. We will set this threshold at 90k and remove columns above that limit. For the remaining rows with NA's we will for the time being leave these out. CreditGrade has NAs for the years 2009 and onwards, but is a very useful feature which we will utilize during our analysis. Therefore, when this is part of a visual, be aware of the number of rows or the sum of observations as it will be different than for the visuals not using this feature.
  • Error in data: we inspect df.describe and df.info. By visually inspecting min/max values of the data and data types we don't spot anything particularly unusual. In a data wrangling project a lot more time would be spent here, but we will stick to the major concepts to enable us to analyze, explore and explain our data visually. Some ordinal objects are likely nominal and will need to be encoded for visualizations, such as IncomeRange and CreditGrades. LoanOriginationDate is an object and will be converted to datetime. We will also feature engineer BorrowerRate as an additional categorical variable.

Step 3) Cleaning Data¶

  1. Remove columns with too many NAs
  2. Re-encode variables of interest from nominal to ordinal
  3. Convert relevant datetime objects from string to date
  4. Feature engineering of BorrowerRate

Takeaway 1 (bivariate):

  • BorrowerRate and LoanOriginalAmount has a box-like shape, which means there is no clear trend between these two features. However, it is interesting to note that the highest borrowerrates are for very low loan amounts. Also, the highest loan amounts have quite low borrowerrates (most points below a rate of 0.2). This gives us an impression of good borrowers can loan high with good conditions, while bad borrowers can be forced to loan low with bad conditions.
  • StatedMonthlyIncome and LoanOriginalAMount has a skewed-like shape. A vertical line of points are at 10^-1, and does not tell us anything (perhaps bad data). The data between 10^2 and 10^^6 tells us something different. The highest loan amounts (loans > 25k) are only seen for StatedMonthlyIncome above 10^4. This gives us an impression of strict criterias for the highest of loans. We also see horizontal stripes of data at LoanOriginalAmount of 5k, 10k, 15k, 20k and 25k. This gives us the impression either credit limits or searched for credit are given at certain intervals.

Next we will look at violin plots to describe relationships between quantitative and qualitative variables.

In [250]:
def Loan_plots(var1):
    '''Function which takes as input a quantiative variable (preferably LoanOriginalAmount or BorrowerRate) 
    and provides as output 4 violin-type plots for IsBorrowerHomeOwner, CreditGrade, EmploymentStatus and IncomeRange'''
    
    fig, ((ax1, ax2), (ax3, ax4)) = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize=(14,10))

    # Ax1: Plot 1
    ax1.set_title(f'{var1} by IsBorrowerHomeowner')
    ax1 = sns.violinplot(data=df, y=var1, x='IsBorrowerHomeowner', color='tab:blue', inner='quartile', ax=ax1)
    ax1.set(xlabel=None)
    [l.set_color('lightgrey') for l in ax1.lines]
    
    # Ax2: Plot 2
    ax2 = sns.violinplot(data=df, y=var1, x='CreditGrade', color='tab:blue', inner='quartile', ax=ax2)
    ax2.set_title(f'{var1} by CreditGrade')
    ax2.set(xlabel=None, ylabel=None)
    [l.set_color('lightgrey') for l in ax2.lines]

    # Ax3: Plot 3
    ax3 = sns.violinplot(data=df, y=var1, x='EmploymentStatus', color='tab:blue', inner='quartile', ax=ax3)
    ax3.set_title(f'{var1} by EmploymentStatus')
    ax3.set(xlabel=None)
    ax3.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=35)
    [l.set_color('lightgrey') for l in ax3.lines]

    # Ax4: Plot 4
    ax4 = sns.violinplot(data=df, y=var1, x='IncomeRange', color='tab:blue', inner='quartile', ax=ax4)
    ax4.set_title(f'{var1} by IncomeRange')
    ax4.set(xlabel=None, ylabel=None)
    ax4.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=35)
    [l.set_color('lightgrey') for l in ax4.lines]
In [235]:
Loan_plots('LoanOriginalAmount')

Takeaway 2 (bivariate): Above we plotted 4 violin plots, each with LoanOriginalAmount against another feature. Let's explore some of the distributions.

  • IsBorrowerHomeowner has an interesting distribution for True and False. False has the lowest quantiles, with the highest distribution with a LoanOriginalAmount around 5k. We see the same distribution here as before, in that pockets of distributions also appear at rounded values of 10k, 15k, 20k and 25k. For IsBorrowerHomeowner=True, we find that the median of LoanOriginalAmount is noticably higher. There are fewer observations with loan amounts less than 5k, but more observations at 15k, 20k, 25k and 35k. This gives us the indication that being a homeowner will affect what loan amount you are getting (perhaps the home acting as security here for the borrower, thus giving the borrower a better rate).
  • The CreditGrade violinplot only shows us data pre-2009, but also gives us some interesting insights. On one hand, grades "AA" and "A" are so similar that we don't spot any noticable difference, but comparing distributions for those two grades to the "B" and "C" distributions, we spot a noticable difference in that "B" and "C" are worse off on the loan. Overall there is a noticable trend from grades "AA" all the way to "NC" in that the worse the CreditGrade gets, the denser the distribution gets at the low-end of LoanOriginalAmount, and the shorter the high-tail gets. From this we draw the insight that a good CreditGrade will increase a borrowers chance for a higher loan, while a bad rating will give you a bad chance.
  • For EmploymentStatus we spot something similar: being "Self-employed" or "Employed" will increase your chances for a high loan, while working "part-time", "not employed" or "retired" will lower your chances (observed by distributions and tail heights).
  • For IncomeRange we see the same type of trend. A high income (50k-75k, 75k-100k or 100k+) has a widely distributed LoanOriginalAmount, while low income (0k, 0k-25k) and no data (not displayed, not employed) has a higher low-end distribution.

Conclusions¶

  • The worse the credit grade, the lower the chance for a good borrower rate and high loan amount. A grade worse than "B" will give the borrower a very low chance for the best rate.
  • Being a homeowner increases your chance for a higher loan, and also gives the borrower a better chance for a good borrower rate.
  • Being employed is a good thing, both for the borrowers rate and for getting a higher loan amount.
  • The borrowers income will affect the chance for a low rate and a high loan amount.

Finally, let's revisit our research questions.

Does it matter who you are for what loan amount you are getting?¶

Yes it does. If you are a high-earning professional, with a house and good liquidity you are more likely to get a good rate and be approved for a high loan amount.

Who gets the best borrowerrate and why?¶

An individual scoring well on analyzed attributes throughout this report has a higher chance for a good borrowerrate. The best rates are generally given to those with "AA" or "A" ratings who also do well on other features. There could be many reasons for this, some include probability of default for a given loan, borrower value to company and more. As we saw in our visuals, there were some exceptions to this general trend. A possible explanation for this could be special membership qualifying for good terms or similar, bypassing the regular rate-rules.
